\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Wide-band EEG activity:
\end_layout

\end_inset

 EEG signals were band-pass filtered between 3 Hz and 26 Hz, in order to
 filter DC drift and part of the artifacts (e.g., facial muscle activity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fatourechi07"

\end_inset

) that may pollute them.
 Their power is then computed before being displayed.
 This corresponds to unspecific brain signals, hence they were labeled as
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

raw
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 signals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Sensorimotor activity:
\end_layout

\end_inset

 EEG signals were first band-pass filtered in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 band (16-24Hz), a brain rhythm highly involved in sensorimotor tasks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pfurtscheller99b"

\end_inset

.
 Then, they were spatially filtered, i.e., the signals from several neighboring
 EEG sensors were combined in order to enhance the signal of interest.
 In particular, we used and displayed Laplacian spatial filters around electrode
s C3, C4 and Cz.
 This enabled the users to visualize EEG activity changes due to movements
 of the left hand, right hand and feet.
 Indeed, it is known that the power of EEG signals in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 rhythm decreases in electrodes C3/Cz/C4 during right hand/feet/left hand
 movements respectively, and increases just after the end of this movement
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pfurtscheller99b"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Visual activity:
\end_layout

\end_inset

 EEG signals were band-pass filtered in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 band (8-12 Hz), then only electrodes P3, Pz, P4, PO3, POz, PO4, O1, Oz
 and O2 (located on the back of the head, above the neck) were selected
 and displayed.
 These electrodes are indeed located over the visual cortex of the brain,
 i.e., the brain area in charge of visual information processing.
 The amplitude of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 rhythm is actually known to increase while the user is closing his/her
 eyes and is thus not processing any visual information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Niedermeyer05"

\end_inset

.
 To ensure that the user could perceive this increase after he/she reopened
 his/her eyes, the visualization was delayed by 0.5s.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Meditation: on a more exploratory note, we used the synchronization between
 the signals from the anterior and posterior cortex (AFz/Pz), which was
 measured in a 7-28 Hz band with instantaneous phase locking value 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lachaux2000"

\end_inset

.
 There are different outcomes (increase/decrease in synchronization) depending
 on meditation type.
 Mindfulness and body focus practices decrease the synchronization while
 transcendental practice increases it 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lehmann2012"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
EEG signals were acquired with a 32-channels EEG device (made of two g.tec
 g.USBAmp EEG amplifiers).
 This professional-grade system ensured that our prototype had a good signal-to-
noise ratio and accurate electrode location, avoiding unneeded uncertainties.
 Signals were processed in real-time using OpenViBE 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Renard10"

\end_inset

.
 For pipelines 1 to 3, the displayed colors correspond to signal power strength;
 for pipeline 4 they correspond to the degree of synchronization.
\end_layout

